Description: Corroded iron item in the shape of a short and thick nail or peg with one end pointed, the other bent by hammering to create a narrow loop or eye.
Curator's comments: The item is interpreted as a tent-peg in the Museum register, but as a helmet-peak by W.M.F. Petrie, Tanis ii, Nebesheh and Defenneh, p. 77 § 77, p. 110 : "The objects 8 to 11 are difficult to explain; possibly they may be ornaments fort the peaks of helmets...".
Bibliographic references: Petrie 1888 / Tanis. Part II. Nebesheh (Am) and Defenneh (Tahpanhes) (p. 77-78 § 77, p. 110, pl. xxxvii, 8)
Leclère and Spencer 2014 / Tell Dafana Reconsidered: The Archaeology of an Egyptian Frontier Town (p.79, p.185, pl.27)
